faqs:
  - question: "What does HEMA-free gel polish actually mean?"
    answer: "HEMA (2-Hydroxyethyl Methacrylate) is a chemical monomer in most conventional gel polishes that causes allergic reactions in sensitive users. HEMA-free gel polish replaces it with plant-based or alternative monomers that deliver the same adhesion and shine without the sensitization risk. Reactions to HEMA are cumulative — you can develop an allergy after months or years of use even without prior symptoms."

  - question: "Is HEMA-free gel polish as long-lasting as regular gel polish?"
    answer: "Yes, current-generation HEMA-free formulas last just as long. The Sweet Scent plant-based line delivers up to 28 days of wear. The Fleurwee line offers up to 21 days. Early HEMA-free formulas (2020–2022) had adhesion issues, but those have been resolved in today's plant-based formulas."

  - question: "Does HEMA-free gel polish need a special UV lamp?"
    answer: "No. HEMA-free gel polish cures under any standard UV/LED nail lamp. These formulas work with the lamps you already own — no special equipment needed."

  - question: "Can I still react to HEMA-free gel polish if I have sensitive skin?"
    answer: "HEMA is the most common gel allergen, but not the only one. HEMA-free means the specific HEMA monomer is removed — but some users with broad acrylate sensitivities may still react to other formula components. Always do a patch test before full application, especially if you've had previous gel reactions."

  - question: "What is the difference between the Fleurwee and Sweet Scent HEMA-free lines?"
    answer: "Both lines are plant-based and HEMA/HPMA/TPO-free. The Sweet Scent line uses 16.5ml bottles (10% larger), adds 7 natural IFRA-compliant fragrances, and delivers up to 28-day wear. The Fleurwee line uses 15ml bottles, has no fragrance, uses nano-milling technology for smoother self-leveling, and is available in larger color palettes (42 and 52 colors)."

